Description

Nature Breakdown is a core suite of capabilities designed to parse and understand the semantic nature of unstructured clinical or system text. Within this suite, Intent Finder plays a critical role by identifying the underlying user intent behind queries (e.g., recognizing that "find elevated PSA" refers to searching for specific Prostate-Specific Antigen lab results with values greater than a certain threshold).

Currently, the Intent Finder API successfully identifies intents and their components. However, downstream use-cases—such as the Shopping List feature—need more than just semantic understanding. To actually retrieve the relevant data, they need actionable metadata, or retrieval signals.

I want the Intent Finder API to return structured retrieval signals (record types, temporal parameters, and author information) alongside identified intents and components,

So that my application can programmatically determine the exact data sources, time bounds, and filters required to satisfy the user's intent.

Dev Notes:

Temporal needs to be mapped to codes and formula based on Bhavani’s logic

For now, record types will be string so no need to call Concept Coding to get codes. But we need to make sure that they are structurally stored so we can add codes in later.

Acceptance Criteria


API Update: The existing Intent Finder API endpoint is updated to include a new metadata block for "retrieval signals" when an intent requires data pulling.

Payload Structure: 

Allow users to turn on/off this retrieval signal generation

Compatibility: The updated API response remains backward-compatible for clients not yet using the new retrieval signals.

